<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="83944130ae65883552196d27d1f3ff66" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> TTT - Many Riddles   Pt.1<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.94)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025'>Brad "Dr_Diablo" Peck</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 6, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
Well, it’s been a while since I actually decided to write about the brand new set, possibly because of personal laziness, or probably because this set has taken literally forever to get here.  Now that may not be such a bad thing, because even though at first glance many are saying they much preferred the Fellowship block, there is a necessary progression that must take place with the game.  The Two Towers block seems (at least to this player) to be a very deserving and very fitting addition to the game we already love.  Sure there are discrepancies about which Ring to use, the potential of a culture based entirely on “1 vitality” minions, the fact the people don’t like Dwarves, that Elves were meant to fight, and the continuos question of  “Now what exactly am I supposed to do with my Moria deck?”  Well, though I am hardly the epitome of LOTR players, I am someone who thought it would be fun to give my thoughts on the new set, and explain my reactions of each culture and the cards within them.  Oh, and obviously I can’t explain everything I like about the set, but I won’t go cheap on you either.  Ahhhh, now where to start…<br />
<br />
<br />
Well, firstly, many people I have spoken to, or read the thoughts from, think that The Two Towers will either make or break the game as we know it.  They feel Decipher has tried to add too much to the game, and has caused a lot of inconsistencies as compared to the book.  It seems people want to take the game to the level the movies and the book explain it to be, as Frodo and Sam leave on one path, and the rest of the fellowship leave on another.  Now how would this be reflected in the game mechanics?  You could have two separate types of decks, some Ring-bound, others unbound, that show certain characters that were on each path our heroes took.  Well, that would be a good idea, except it would be very limiting, and would kill specific cards are deck themes.  How well would your corruption deck do without a Ring-bearer there?  So Decipher had to work with what they could.  During Frodo’s path to Mordor, he had help from his friends such as Aragorn and Gandalf.  Not physically of course, but because they would distract the Eye of Sauron, he could more easily slip by unnoticed.  And as for the Hunters, well certainly they must have been influenced to do things because of Frodo, and to see that he is successful in his journey by whatever means they could.  Yes, I know they took totally different paths, but the game doesn’t necessarily become inconsistent by having Frodo and Aragorn in your fellowship, as they were headed the same way anyway.  So before you judge the game based on how “inconsistent” it is, first realize that it is a game, and isn’t meant to contradict the books or movie, and secondly remember that Decipher had to work with the previous game mechanics to make this game, and certainly couldn’t change all the rules.  On that note, I will look at 4 of the different cultures this expansion adds to, as well as look at the alternative to the Ring.  <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
THE ONE RING – Cause of many riddles<br />
Like the popular Isildur’s Bane, we are now given a further option to the Ruling Ring version of the One Ring.  The picture on this card is gosh darnit near one of the best pictures I’ve ever seen on a card, and makes me wonder about how cool it would look foiled.  Anyways, enough of the image, and on to the game text.  The Answer to All Riddles is merely the start of another one.  Which ring do I use in my deck?  Well, I think that Isildur’s Bane has become by far the choice of everyone, and this ring will do little to change that.  A vitality bonus of 2 is nice, as is a strength bonus on 2 when Frodo is wearing the ring.  But, unlike Isildur’s Bane you are only adding one burden, and are only adding it during the skirmish phase.  Wait a tick, did I just say you are adding one burden? Oh silly me, I am like many people and read the card through too quickly.  Beware this line “Skirmish: Add a burden to wear The One Ring until the regroup phase.”  So you’re telling me that if I am only to take one wound, I’m still adding two burdens, and I can’t even use it to soak up archery?  To others, it may still seem viable, but to me, I’ll just keep playing Isildur’s Bane until I see a good reason to use the Answer to All Riddles.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
DUNLAND CULTURE – Pillaging and Plundering and everything nice<br />
<br />
Ahh, this is a culture I am dying to try out, and note, I will have a lot to say because they are so new.  Sure they look like weenies at first glance that will be picked off one by one in the archery phase, and individually none of the cards are too impressive.  Note, I said individually.  Together, they can make for some dreadful combinations, and can make even the most prepared fellowship go running in terror.  The Dunlendings require several things to make a deck worthy of tournament play, but the most important being site control.  Site control is TTT biggest change since the fellowship block and will revolutionize many, many shadow decks.  Some minions (such as Dunlending Ransacker) allow you to gain control of a site when you win skirmishes, and others (like Hillman Band) spot another Dunlending Man when the opponent moves again to gain control of a site.  Obviously, the skirmish winning strategy is much easier to pull off, and with Wulf the Dunlending Chieftain down, you could gain control of two sites with one victory.  The controlling a site once they move again in the regroup phase is most easily accomplished with the assistance of No Retreat, as they are forced to face another horde of minions once you force them to move.  Many of the Conditions and Events require you to spot a site you control, or several sites you control to make better use of them, so a Dunlending deck without site control is like a McChicken without the chicken.  <br />
<br />
Another thing Dunland has going for them is the ability to destroy their enemies possessions, or as Decipher was hopefully heading towards, the idea that they are pillagers and destroy everything in their path.  However, most of the possession destroying cards require you at first to win a skirmish, and getting the Dunlendings to the skirmish phase and capable to beat the fellowship is the tricky part.  Many players fear heavy archery still, so Dunlending decks do not seem the type for them.  The most powerful (and costly) minions have a vitality of two, so you’re going to have to find a way to stop the opponent from wounding them to hell and back before the skirmish phase.  There are a couple ways of doing this that will be most common.  Firstly we have Hides, which allows you to spend 2 twilight or discard it to prevent a wound to a Dunlending Man, not to mention you get to draw a card when you play it for better deck cycling.  This card is “money” as the saying goes.  I don’t think you will see too many Dunlending decks that don’t pack four copies of this card.  Secondly, we have Saruman, Rabble-rouser.  Sure he doesn’t have the ability to prevent wounds like the Keeper of Isengard version has, but he can soak up the extra archery wounds at least.  And if there is no archery, he is there to help them win the skirmishes.  And, if he makes it to the regroup a couple other Dunlending Men, you can play No Retreat and watch the opponent have to exert for each Man you have down.  He’ll be popping up in many Dunlending decks too.  The ability I feel will make the most impact with the Dunlendings though is the ability to play another minion for the fierce skirmishes once one of your minions (Dunlending Arsonist and Hillman Mob) wins their first, and the ability of other Dunland minions to go fierce and strength +2 once they have won a skirmish.  This will help to get more minions down, and more chances to plan No Retreat.<br />
<br />
Cards worth using:<br />
No Refuge: Control a site and stack a guy there to get 5 more twilight a turn.  Yes, please.<br />
Hides: Prevents wounds to your minions to either help them get past archery, or live through a skirmish.<br />
War Club: Oh, I’m sorry Aragorn, did you need that sword? And Eomer, I thought you needed a horse.<br />
War Cry of Dunland: Almost as good as Savagery, but you have to win the first one.<br />
Death to the Strawheads: Well, your super fellowship just got a super @$$-whooping.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
DWARVEN CULTURE – I hope you have a lot of cards in your deck.<br />
<br />
Ok, so every since Moria, we knew that Dwarves would be getting the screw-over, right?  Well, though the Dwarf cards certainly are a powerful bunch, they honestly aren’t worth making a deck over.  I know, I know, the Dwarves are fun and very tournament viable, but if Grima comes even close to one, there’s no chance he’ll live too long.  All those possessions and conditions you stack like mad to tank up your Dwarves have all because a huge risk since no Dwarf is Ring-bound.  Ahh well, even though everything now is based on Gimli and tanking him to death, the cards still seems to look like Gimli could be the most deadly member of your fellowship.  His new axe takes the old one a step forward.  Sure it loses his “wound something else” ability, but it gains the ability to boost him up with a lot more power.  And if you use any of the conditions in this set, you’ll have cards sitting on them.  The conditions make for really powerful stuff, but in truth, it may not be worth the effort unless as you may lose a lot of cards you ned sitting on these conditions.  At least if you are ballsy enough to try running through Isengard with a group of Dwarves, you can Start Fror and Farin, and use the new site Plains of Rohan to pull Gimli from your reserve.  And heck, taking a 120 deck into a tournament could be fun, because that’s about the least you will end up with after compensating multiple copies of every card your Dwarves could ever need.<br />
<br />
Also included in this set are several cards (including one version of Gimli himself) that encourage playing him and Legolas together, and re-enact their struggle to out-do each other in kills at the Battle of Helms Deep.  Cards like Khazad Ai-menu and Quick As May Be are really only fitting in the Three Hunters type of deck, which deals with the journeys or Gimli, Legolas and Aragorn.  This deck looks very strong to me were it not for one thing holding me back…. Grima.  He is usable in all deck types, and the Shadow player awaits a chance to blow up a fellowship designed on pumping up a few companions.  It was probably Decipher’s wish to get more players to use skirmish events, and thankfully for the Three Hunters, the skirmish events are plentiful.<br />
<br />
Cards worth using:<br />
Gimli, Lockbearer: Merry and Pippin discard decks will need something to tank the other minions.<br />
Quick As May Be: Spot a Dwarf and Elf companion to wound a minion. And it’s maneuver phase.<br />
From the Armory: Chance to lose something good, but worth it to keep Gimli alive.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
ELVEN CULTURE – Awww, I miss the Lorien Elf<br />
<br />
Well, the elves were given a healthy boost in this expansion, mainly the ability to live through a skirmish.  You are given many people to work with here, and although some lose their archery bonus when bearing a bow, they prove more than effective when fighting hand-to-hand.  The Naith have made their presence known, as the Elves get ready with their swords and bows to cause some destruction.  Although in the common deck most of these cards have no place, in an Elf-only deck you would have to worry less than before, as Lorien Elves will not make their “2-vitality” presence felt any more.  Finally people who bring their Elven decks to tournaments are going to feel ashamed once their little elves get smashed around at site 4, because that won’t be as frequent with these guys.  Let’s take one example: Erethon, using an Elven Bow and an Elven Sword is strength 8, vitality 3, damage +1, and can exert or discard 2 cards to make the minion he skirmishes a strength –1.  Not too bad at all, and in the Elf only decks, he’ll have plenty of pumpers to make sure he wins.<br />
<br />
Decipher is actually using most of these cards to encourage an Elf-only deck, since many require you to spot 2 or 3 elves for them to work.  And don’t let the past influence the present, Elf decks will work.  Trust me on it.  Archery isn’t even a necessity (although it’ll help out) because of all the cards making them so good.  Supporting Fire adds 2 strength or 3 if you spot 3 Elf companions.  Flashing Steel exerts an Elf to make the minion he skirmishes strength –3.  Lembas can reconcile your hand in the regroup, so you can double-move with hopefully more helper cards.  And like Gimli, we have the certain Legolas cards that only work in the Three Hunters type of deck.  Legolas, Dauntless Hunter is actually one of my favourite cards in the set, and starting him, Merry and Pippin, and then pulling Aragorn first turn seems to be a very viable way of weakening the opponent and making him use his twilight more effectively.  <br />
<br />
Cards worth using:<br />
Legolas, Dauntless Hunter: Not a card for most decks, but when used right, he is very valuable.<br />
Alliance Reforged: Since the beginning of TCGs and CCGs, cycling proved most important.<br />
Company of Archers: Discard the condition they put down during their shadow phase.  Not bad.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
GANDALF – Didn’t he die?<br />
<br />
Well, the Gandalf culture leaves very much the same influence on the game as it always has: If you want to use Gandalf, you better pay ready to pay for it.  The reason Gandalf was not as popular as other companions prior to now was because, well, he cost a lot, his events cost a lot, his conditions cost a lot, and his possessions cost a lot.  But at least when he adds to the pool, he’s taking something away from it too.  No, I don’t mean he pulls twilight out, I mean that the twilight makes him more powerful.  I guess it all starts with Gandalf, The White Wizard, who becomes a power 10 monster before any adders if you can spot three twilight.  Give him a staff, and you not only add another vitality, but by spotting 2 twilight, he gets damage +2.  Now the question arises, how do you get twilight in there.  And the answer, well, you’re playing Gandalf, so it’s easy.  Keep You Forked Tongue is one of my favourite cards in the set simply because it can work with Gandalf as well, in case there’s that one minion pumped even to the point you can’t beat him.  Mithrandir! Mithrandir! lets you wound those little swarming guys, and adds 3 to the pool.  Have Patience is a great way of healing Gandalf or whoever else has been taking the beatings.  And Task Was Not Done lets you kill off the minions you wounded during the regroup phase.  In short, if you are willing to devote a lot of cards to him, and aren’t too afraid to add to the pool, Gandalf is your man.<br />
<br />
Cards worth using:<br />
Well, check any of the cards I mentioned above.<br />
Treebeard: He’s nice in any deck, because a power 12 ally at site 8 can prevent you from more losses.<br />
Under The Living Earth: I mean, you’re adding the twilight, why not take serious advantage of it.  +5 and not unique!<br />
<br />
<br />
This article has drawn on for far too long, much longer than I had originally anticipated.  I will make a second and possibly third part to it, but for now, I’m going to start working on my decks.  I hope I was at least a tiny bit helpful, and obviously I couldn’t give my thoughts on how the cultures work, since I am only getting my boxes later today.  Now I am off to figure out which Free Peoples side to play as, and how exactly I am going to put together my Easterling/Nazgul burdening deck.  Hope you guys enjoyed my thoughts.  Thanks.<br />
<br />
<br />
